From his previous work, Bob Odenkirk seemed like such an unusual choice to play an action hero, but oh god, it seems he's friggin' brilliant at it !!! When this first popped up on Netflix, I watched it out of curiosity. A couple months later, all I could remember was the basic plot and that I'd thought it was really good, so I just watched it again........ Yep. It's still good. :D  It's refreshing to see an "Old fashioned" action film these days, where no one's trying to cram "Woken" philosophies down your throat, or trying to crow bar some agenda into the storyline.  I'm happy to see that the studio went with the classic plot of "Wronged man seeks revenge", with guns, explosions, cars, and bodies dropping like flies...... it's the sort of movie related escapism an old fashioned guy like me misses.

During VietNam, the 'Death Cards' were a real occurrence, always depicted as an ace of spades with a skull and crossbones in the spade. The movie, as to not takeaway from the soldiers of VietNam, came up with this offshoot variation; 7 of clubs and 2 of Diamonds tattoo. The other set depicted was 8 of hearts and 3 of diamonds cufflinks. What does that all mean? Both of those sets of cards, if dealt to you are the worst cards you can receive in Texas Hold'em. There's no playing those cards, just fold your hand, because you're out.

Just watched the movie, and it has to be the best parody of another film I have ever seen.  **spoilers below, so stop reading if you haven't watched**   The badass killer who goes dormant.  The Russian son who tempts him out of retirement.  The rage-induced rampage he goes on releasing the nerve.  The hair-raising kills he gets from doing what he does best.  The final one-on-one with the Russian father/mob boss.  The peace and tranquility in the end, now happy with a family to call his home.   This was one of the best movies I've seen in a long time, and I hope other movies will follow it.

Gave that movie a try without any expectations, besides thinking it could be good.  Knew Bob Odenkirk from BREAKING BAD.   The beginning was cool. The repetitive days, actions right away set the tone for me. I felt sorry for Hutch already about his miserable life. Something had to give at some point though, lol.   The music in this movie is pretty good. Loved it.  There is lots of action. Shooting, fighting, explosions & blood. The violence is present big time. There is a comedy side also, which is always nice. The story is simple with no big surprises.  Bob Odenkirk gave, imo, a good performance. The rest of the acting, by others, is o.k. no big roles here.  So, I was happily surprised about that movie. Enjoyed it. It was very entertaining to me. Could have watched a bit more.  Thought the movie was short at 1H26. It flows really smoothly.  Could there be a NOBODY #2? Maybe. A big thumbs up from me.

Spoiler - Spoiler - Spoiler - Spoiler I really enjoyed watching this movie, thereÂ´s a lot of unconventional action - not the usual mainstream Hollywood crap - however the movie has its flaws too. LetÂ´s take the example where the russian mob comes to his house the night he made lasagna for his family and talks about going on vacation to Italy. Why the fuck would the Russian mob come to his house - driving in a convoy of 10 cars - like the most visible thing they can do? I bet you could see from Mars that 10 cars were approaching the house. Why not just send ONE man to liquidate him - or shoot him when he leaves his home for work? There are other examples in the movie that are just unrealistic and just reduce the quality of an otherwise great movie.

I saw this movie last night. I've never watched "Breaking Bad" or "Better Call Saul" so I am unfamiliar with the characters that he's played. The movie was a joyride, a violent nutty one, but so well done. It was almost as if Tarantino had a hand in it, but not. Most of the action scenes were like an opera. The cameras were placed everywhere, while music played, and the action was fluid.  Without getting all "critic" about it, it wasn't just unpredictable in some ways, but again, so well orchestrated. Reminded me of The Kingsman's action sequences.  There are a lot of nobodies out there, and this movie unleashed one of the nuttiest version.  So, I'm open to questions.

So if you're like me, an aging gen-x'er, this movie goes like this...  Martin Blank tried to keep his life together with his HS Sweetheart.  Didn't work out.  Knowing what he did, and that someone might come for him someday, they parted as friends.  But he never quit striving for that bit of normalcy, so he married again.  Became the middle-class American everyone expected him to be.  Entered his fifties.  Had a couple of wonderful children along the way.  But then it all caught up with him.  The mess he left in Grosse Point, all the previous checks he'd written, someone came to collect on those.  But thirty years later?  Who is Martin Blank?  Eh.  He's Nobody.

I was into it until the spy/hitman twist. I think the idea of a social satire where the protagonist has to deal with the fallout of a home invasion and deal with his suppressed violent urges/desire to appear masculine would have been a far more interesting film. The trailers gives the impression that the movie was fliting with an interesting concept, but decided to go a more conventional route with it instead. What they basically did was took A History of violence, took away the interesting aspects of it (the characterization and grim/somber tone) and turned it into a more marketable action/comedy.

I just realised what this is!  Or at least what it could be.   This is the rebirth of Trinity.  "My Name Is Nobody".  First you have Westerns, then you have Spagetti Westerns. Here we had Action Films, now we have Spagetti (?) Action films. Okay fine, the analogy isn't perfect, as it's not a reduced budget, nor shot in Italy, but the idea of the comedic everyman hero character being underestimated is fantastic, and it feels very much like it's poking fun at the more serious action tropes to a degree.
